The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Crompton to split stock in 1:5 ratio

 OUR CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, May 23: Crompton Greaves is going for a stock split. The board has recommended a share split in the ratio of 1:5, where each share of Rs 10 will be divided into five shares of Rs 2 each. 

 It also proposed to increase the authorised share capital to Rs 125 crore from Rs 60 crore, subject to shareholders approval at the forthcoming annual general meeting of the company. 

 Crompton Greavess scrip gained 1.59 per cent on Dalal Street today to close at Rs 1,031 against the previous close of Rs 1,014.85. 

 The total traded volume of shares was 29,093. 

 The electrical engineering major, part of the BM Thapar group, has posted a 37.73 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 56.10 crore for the fourth quarter ended March 31 compared with Rs 40.73 crore in the corresponding previous quarter. 

 Earnings for fiscal 2006 stood at Rs 163.05 crore against Rs 114.78 crore in 2004-05. Total income rose to Rs 2,553.33 crore from Rs 1,999.40 crore. 

 The group has posted earnings of Rs 232.03 crore on a total income of Rs 4,191.76 crore during 2005-06. 

 In April, Ballarpur Industries Ltd chairman L.M. Thapar passed on the baton to nephew Gautam Thapar, who is currently the vice-chairman and managing director. Thapar senior will step down in July and thereafter become chairman emeritus of the company.

 Gautam controls the operations of Crompton Greaves. Apart from this, some of the other erstwhile Bilt Group companies like Bilt Chemicals, renamed Solaris ChemTech, and Global Green are also under him. 




